 Cindy was a mother and friend to many that knew her. She struggled with cancer for two years. I met her the first day of school for my Daughter Jenica. Her daughter and mine became close friends quickly. Cindy was always there for any school event, volunteer work and child that needed a mother’s touch when they were in school. I have yet to meet a mother so dedicated to the social life and education of her child. I can see now I wished to be like her. Cindy first learned she had cancer in the summer before her daughter entered kinder. She had all the operations and Chemotherapy she was required to get. All tests came back in the clear and she dove right into her normal life of making treats for snack time and decorating for the fall carnival. Everyone in the neighborhood knew her and knew how great of a mom she was. They never would think twice about letting their child come spend the night for a slumber party of calling her to ask if she could babysit last minute. Last fall we all were sad to hear the cancer had returned. I could see in her eyes she would not give up the fight when she told me about it, and she didn’t. Every local doctor told her treatment would not help. They refused to give her any more chemotherapy and in other words let her know it was time to make “arrangements”. She went to every specialist in the state and event traveled as far as Seattle and the Mayo Clinic. I was one of the many moms who watched Katie (her daughter) while she would go off to another doctor with hopes to, as she said “Live to see my daughter get married”. We prayed with her silently hoping to hear the same. When she finally returned home she was not the same woman I remembered seeing last. The happiness drained from her once cheerful blue eyes, she had lost 50 lbs and had a hard time walking due to the cancer spreading from her cervix to her legs. I began to see less and less of her in school events and holiday parties. Until I heard she had taken to bed and was given a feeding tube that later had to be removed due to GI problems. When I saw my daughter come home on Tuesday she looked at me with tears in her eyes and told me “Mommy, Cindy died” and walked over to me and hugged me tight. My chest felt as if I was stabbed. I held in my urge to cry and wiped her tears. Telling her “Jenica, Cindy is in heaven now, she doesn’t hurt any more. She is happy and flying with the angels.” Her smile was huge. Later when I tucked her into bed I cried. I cried for hours. I questioned why such a wonderful woman, great mom and hard working wife had to go so soon. Why couldn’t she live long enough to see her daughter get married? Better yet her grandchildren get married as well? And then I remembered I answered my own question earlier “She’s in heaven now, and she doesn’t hurt any more. She is happy and flying with the angles” and then I smiled.<br><br>Please make sure you get checked yearly for cancer in ANY form. Just because you feel fine doesn't mean anything can't be wrong. Don't let it be too late to still give it a good fight. Cervical, breast and ovarin cancer aka the silent killers, can be detected with regular check ups.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/ucyranodivinewind.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cyrano Divinewind</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>THogg's Master</span><br>  Posts: 18<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/25/02 5:27:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub28.ezboard.com/fdrinal28133frm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2858.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   She is in better place...........</span><hr size=1> /cry<br><br>My deepest Condolances to the family. I am sure she is in better place now.<br><br>Cyrano Divinewind<br>Evoker of Nine Clouds <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub28.ezboard.com/ucyranodivinewind.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cy